---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const slug = 'ophthalmology-ent';
const displayName = 'Ophthalmology & ENT';

const drugs = (drugsData as any[]).filter(
  (d: any) => (d.organ_systems || []).includes(slug)
);
const drugCount = drugs.length;
---
<SchemaLayout title="Ophthalmology & ENT Pharmacology" schema="organ-systems" description="Drugs classified under the Ophthalmology & ENT organ system">

  <div class="mb-6">
    <div class="breadcrumbs text-sm mb-4">
      <ul>
        <li><a href={`${base}schemas/01-organ-systems/`} class="link">Organ Systems</a></li>
        <li>Ophthalmology & ENT</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold text-base-content mb-2">Ophthalmology & ENT</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">{drugCount} drug{drugCount !== 1 ? 's' : ''} in this system</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>Ophthalmological and otolaryngological pharmacology within this reference encompasses agents with significant ophthalmic, otic, and nasal applications, including several systemic drugs with important ocular toxicity profiles. Key ocular pharmacological targets include carbonic anhydrase in the ciliary body (acetazolamide, dorzolamide), prostaglandin FP receptors in the trabecular meshwork (latanoprost, bimatoprost), alpha-2 receptors (brimonidine), and beta receptors in the ciliary epithelium (timolol). In the ENT context, antihistamines and intranasal corticosteroids are the dominant drug classes for allergic rhinitis, while decongestants (pseudoephedrine, oxymetazoline) act on alpha-1 receptors in nasal mucosa. Systemic agents with clinically important ocular toxicity include chloroquine and hydroxychloroquine (macular toxicity requiring annual ophthalmological surveillance), amiodarone (corneal microdeposits), tamoxifen (macular degeneration), and ethambutol (optic neuritis). Nursing priorities include correct ophthalmic drop instillation technique with nasolacrimal occlusion to minimize systemic absorption, monitoring for systemic effects of topical agents (particularly topical beta-blockers causing bronchospasm and bradycardia in susceptible patients), and patient education on ophthalmic drop sequencing.</p>
    <p>Glaucoma pharmacotherapy aims to reduce intraocular pressure (IOP) to prevent optic nerve damage and visual field loss. Prostaglandin analogs (latanoprost, bimatoprost, travoprost) increase uveoscleral outflow and are the most effective single agents, reducing IOP by 25 to 35 percent; they are administered once nightly and notable adverse effects include iris and periocular pigmentation changes and eyelash growth. Topical beta-blockers (timolol, betaxolol) reduce aqueous humor production by blocking beta receptors on the ciliary epithelium; while topically administered, enough drug is systemically absorbed via the nasolacrimal duct to cause bradycardia and bronchoconstriction. Nurses must specifically ask patients whether they are using any eye drops when assessing unexplained bradycardia or asthma exacerbation. Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors reduce aqueous production by inhibiting carbonic anhydrase II in the ciliary epithelium; oral acetazolamide provides greater IOP reduction than topical dorzolamide but causes dose-dependent metabolic acidosis, hypokalemia, renal calculi, and sulfonamide cross-reactivity adverse effects.</p>
    <p>Otic pharmacology primarily involves topical preparations for otitis externa and cerumen management, but several systemic agents have clinically critical ototoxic profiles. Aminoglycoside antibiotics (gentamicin, tobramycin, amikacin) cause cochlear and vestibular hair cell destruction through reactive oxygen species generation, with high-frequency hearing loss preceding lower frequencies; risk is increased by cumulative dose, renal impairment, concurrent loop diuretics, and genetic susceptibility (mitochondrial 12S rRNA variants). Nurses administering aminoglycosides must monitor trough levels (less than 1 mcg/mL for gentamicin and tobramycin) and inquire about tinnitus and balance disturbance at each administration. Loop diuretics (furosemide) at high IV doses cause reversible ototoxicity through disruption of the endolymphatic electrical potential, particularly when combined with aminoglycosides. Cisplatin causes irreversible sensorineural hearing loss in 30 to 60 percent of patients; audiological assessment is performed before each cisplatin cycle, and the severity of hearing loss may necessitate dose modification or discontinuation.</p>
  </div>

  {drugs.length === 0 && (
    <div class="alert alert-info mb-6">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="stroke-current shrink-0 w-6 h-6"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path></svg>
      <span>No drugs are currently classified under this organ system. Check back as more drug data is added.</span>
    </div>
  )}

  {drugs.length > 0 && (
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      {drugs.map((drug: any) => (
        <div class={`card card-compact bg-base-100 shadow border border-base-200 ${drug.ismp_high_alert ? 'border-l-4 border-l-error' : ''}`}>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-start gap-1 mb-1">
              <h2 class="card-title text-base font-semibold capitalize mr-auto">
                <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">
                  {drug.generic_name}
                </a>
              </h2>
              {drug.prototype_for && (
                <span class="badge badge-success badge-sm shrink-0">PROTOTYPE</span>
              )}
              {drug.ismp_high_alert && (
                <span class="badge badge-error badge-sm shrink-0">HIGH ALERT</span>
              )}
              {drug.black_box_warnings && drug.black_box_warnings.length > 0 && (
                <span class="badge badge-warning badge-sm shrink-0">BBW</span>
              )}
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-base-content/60 mb-1">
              <span class="font-medium">{drug.drug_class}</span>
              {drug.subclass && <span> &mdash; {drug.subclass}</span>}
            </p>
            {drug.mechanism_summary && (
              <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70 line-clamp-3">{drug.mechanism_summary}</p>
            )}
            <div class="card-actions justify-end mt-2">
              <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="btn btn-xs btn-outline btn-primary">Profile</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  )}

</SchemaLayout>
